00:05:22.230 --> 00:05:25.770
- My whole research program is around

00:05:25.770 --> 00:05:28.127
how are memory stored in the brain.

00:05:28.127 --> 00:05:30.540
And so, why do we think about the brain?

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.470
It's because we know for
many studies in humans

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:36.330
that when there are lesions in the brain,

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:39.130
for example in the part of
the brain called hippocampus.

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:40.230
It's called hippocampus

00:05:40.230 --> 00:05:43.060
because it looks a little like a seahorse.

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:44.300
When there's a stroke there,

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:47.580
when there's some kind of an injury,

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:50.810
the person with that
injury can no longer form

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:52.240
long-term memory.

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:54.570
So their experiences are never actually

00:05:54.570 --> 00:05:56.623
encoded into a long=term memory.

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:00.640
Similarly, other parts of the brain

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:02.150
when there are lesions there,

00:06:02.150 --> 00:06:06.490
there are alterations in
a way that that individual

00:06:06.490 --> 00:06:09.598
perceive the world will behave,

00:06:09.598 --> 00:06:12.100
will encode information,

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:16.840
and will in turn transform
that information into memories,

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:20.667
and those memories are
thus stored in the brain.

00:06:20.667 --> 00:06:24.130
And we really wanna understand
how it is, that experience,

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:26.200
how our everyday experience

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:31.210
is encoded in that region of the brain.

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:33.230
So, the human brain is shown here.

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:37.013
It's a three-pound organ in our head.

00:06:38.140 --> 00:06:41.170
And about well over 100 years ago,

00:06:41.170 --> 00:06:44.400
Ramon Y Cajal who was a
Spanish neuroscientist

00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:48.110
literally sitting at his
kitchen table with a microscope,

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:50.440
using this beautiful staining method

00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:53.530
where you could see individual
nerve cells in the brain.

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:55.920
This was from a pigeon brain.

00:06:55.920 --> 00:06:59.300
He saw this and he
realized from looking at it

00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:01.470
that there were all these different cells,

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:03.190
and it wasn't a whole gamish.

00:07:03.190 --> 00:07:06.120
At the time, it was
thought to be a syncytium.

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:08.540
And you looked at it and
he saw here's one cell

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:13.540
that has this incredible
elaborate arbor of processes.

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:16.500
And he saw that they contacted each other

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:18.340
at specific sites.

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:22.600
And just by looking at that
structure of the brain,

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:25.640
he came up with the idea that

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:28.840
those connections between nerve cells

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:31.633
might be the site where
memories are stored.

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:36.820
So this was not any kind of
molecular biology, no genetics.

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:40.860
It was really by looking at the form

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:44.623
that the neuro cells existed in the brain.

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:47.940
So that's well over 100 years,

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:50.110
and we now know that he was right,

00:07:50.110 --> 00:07:53.590
that there's something that
we call synoptic plasticity.

00:07:53.590 --> 00:07:56.640
Those sites of contact,
they're called synapse,

00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:59.373
they're the re-clasping together,

00:08:00.250 --> 00:08:03.170
that those sites, those
synoptic connections

00:08:03.170 --> 00:08:05.033
change with our experience.

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:09.060
And in fact, while you're sitting here,

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:13.320
if you remember anything
at the end of this evening,

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:15.820
you will have a different
structure in your brain.

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:19.590
Those nerve cells will be
forming different synapses.

00:08:19.590 --> 00:08:21.850
You will have gain some new synapses,

00:08:21.850 --> 00:08:25.520
and we have a lot of really, to me,

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:29.080
beautiful empowering tools
for standing to understand

00:08:29.080 --> 00:08:31.290
how that process works.

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:34.170
That was over a hundred years ago.

00:08:34.170 --> 00:08:39.050
Now we can use tools using
genetics and molecular biology

00:08:39.050 --> 00:08:41.540
where we can label nerve cells

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:44.720
using a lot of different
fluorescent proteins.

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:46.210
This is in the part of the brain

00:08:46.210 --> 00:08:49.430
called the cerebellum in
the back of your head,

00:08:49.430 --> 00:08:50.500
in the back of your brain

00:08:50.500 --> 00:08:53.140
that's involved in coordination.

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:55.600
Motor skills, motor learning.

00:08:55.600 --> 00:08:58.360
These are beautiful
cerebellar Purkinje neurons

00:08:58.360 --> 00:08:59.550
that form these arbors,

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:02.090
and here you can label individual neurons

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:03.880
with different fluorescent proteins,

00:09:03.880 --> 00:09:05.680
so you can see what their structure is

00:09:05.680 --> 00:09:07.453
and how they contact one another.

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:10.920
Here's a nerve cell that's in your cortex,

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:13.550
the part of your brain that's required for

00:09:13.550 --> 00:09:15.530
what we call executive function,

00:09:15.530 --> 00:09:17.963
making sure that you
behave professionally.

00:09:19.281 --> 00:09:24.270
And we can label the whole neuron in red,

00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:26.620
but we can label the individual synapses,

00:09:26.620 --> 00:09:30.570
those places where nerve cells
communicate with one another,

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:32.410
and where there's that plasticity

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:36.470
where memories can be stored
with that green label.

00:09:36.470 --> 00:09:41.310
And so, over time, one can
look at those individual cells,

00:09:41.310 --> 00:09:45.790
you can do something where
you can use genetics to label

00:09:45.790 --> 00:09:49.280
multiple cells in what's
called the neural circuit,

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:50.720
and why is this important.

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:55.360
It's because the human brain
has about 100 billion neurons,

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:57.950
and it has about 100 trillion synapses.

00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:00.613
It's this incredibly complex circuit.

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:05.970
It's the circuitry that
underlies our perception,

00:10:05.970 --> 00:10:09.000
our emotions, our ability to remember,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.600
the way we behave, the way we move,

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:14.030
and all of that changes over time.

00:10:14.030 --> 00:10:16.650
It's hard wired when we're born,

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:20.110
but it undergoes this dynamic remodeling.

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:23.600
And so the way that I think about memory

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:27.440
is how does that dynamic
remodeling happen.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:29.980
We can even take nerve cells, for example,

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:32.430
at a very high powered microscope,

00:10:32.430 --> 00:10:34.480
looking at it, stimulating it,

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:38.080
and you can watch over time that these new

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:41.640
sites of contact, these
new synapses will grow.

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:43.890
So that kind of plasticity
is something that

00:10:43.890 --> 00:10:46.550
we can now begin to really understand

00:10:46.550 --> 00:10:49.430
what are the underlying
molecular mechanisms.

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:51.010
And by understanding that,

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:54.910
the hope is really that
we'll be able to address

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:57.850
disease that involve memory,

00:10:57.850 --> 00:10:59.170
whether those are things like

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:00.920
post traumatic stress disorder

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:02.780
or things like Alzheimer's disease

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:05.060
where there's a loss of memory.

00:11:05.060 --> 00:11:07.700
And the other thing
that studies like this,

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:11.480
they've revealed over a history of work

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:14.100
for many different people across the globe

00:11:14.100 --> 00:11:17.580
are three principles that I
think are really important.

00:11:17.580 --> 00:11:19.550
For us as human beings.

00:11:19.550 --> 00:11:21.400
One of them is that
there's something called

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:23.800
a critical period in childhood,

00:11:23.800 --> 00:11:26.660
and it's really the period
up through adolescence

00:11:26.660 --> 00:11:29.160
at which that kind of synapses plasticity

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:31.140
is particularly powerful.

00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:34.310
And so our early childhood experiences

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:36.940
are stored in changes in the connectivity

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:39.410
of deep brain structures

00:11:39.410 --> 00:11:42.100
in what's called the limbic system

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:46.210
that very powerfully alters
the way that we see the world,

00:11:46.210 --> 00:11:50.460
and hence children who
have traumatic experiences

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:52.770
will carry that with them,

00:11:52.770 --> 00:11:55.930
and then their subsequent experiences

00:11:55.930 --> 00:11:57.423
will be altered by that.

00:11:58.450 --> 00:12:00.970
Another features is that emotion

00:12:00.970 --> 00:12:04.790
has a powerful impact on
that synaptic plasticity.

00:12:04.790 --> 00:12:08.350
So, I'm gonna age myself here,

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:11.893
but if you remember, and I
was really young at the time.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:17.430
I remember when JFK was killed,

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:19.130
and I remember my mom crying,

00:12:19.130 --> 00:12:21.350
and I remember that situation quite well.

00:12:21.350 --> 00:12:23.810
I really remember when Price Di died

00:12:23.810 --> 00:12:24.880
because it was this very,

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:26.470
there was a lot of emotion.

00:12:26.470 --> 00:12:30.760
And that emotion tends to really enhance

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:32.900
plasticity and memory formation.

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:34.860
So there's a lot of work on

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:39.860
what's the role of emotion,
and attention, and alertness

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:42.650
in forming memories.

00:12:42.650 --> 00:12:47.450
Another important feature
of memory is repetition,

00:12:47.450 --> 00:12:49.480
and I think any student knows this.

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:53.520
There's lots of work
that shows that if you

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:55.270
wanna learn how to play the piano

00:12:55.270 --> 00:12:58.610
and you practice once
a week for two hours,

00:12:58.610 --> 00:13:02.763
that's not as good as practicing
every day for half an hour.

00:13:03.675 --> 00:13:08.440
So that kind of repetition
is a way that our brains

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:11.120
are able to promote that plasticity

00:13:11.120 --> 00:13:13.410
and that storage of memory.

00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:17.060
So these, I think of myself as

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:20.590
somewhat of what I call a reductionist.

00:13:20.590 --> 00:13:22.673
I think of what's the real,

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:27.270
the concrete storage,

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:30.650
what we call the n-gram
of memory in the brain.

00:13:30.650 --> 00:13:35.310
And yet I recognize that this
doesn't necessarily capture

00:13:35.310 --> 00:13:38.380
what our own individual
experiences of memory are,

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:40.970
and yet it does tell me
something very important

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:43.610
about my own experience of memory,

00:13:43.610 --> 00:13:45.720
which is that it's dynamic,

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:49.370
that all of my past experiences

00:13:49.370 --> 00:13:51.630
are changing the way that I'm perceiving

00:13:52.700 --> 00:13:56.480
any ongoing experience,
and that that in turn

00:13:56.480 --> 00:13:59.760
means that memory can be
quite fallible and subjective.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:03.150
It's not a recording of reality.

00:14:03.150 --> 00:14:05.680
It's an act somewhere between recording

00:14:06.990 --> 00:14:11.510
and sort of creativity that
comes with your entire past

00:14:11.510 --> 00:14:13.830
experience as a human being.

00:14:13.830 --> 00:14:17.540
And so I think that that
understanding of the biology

00:14:17.540 --> 00:14:21.050
and understanding how the biology explains

00:14:21.050 --> 00:14:26.050
that dynamic, subjective
emotional component of memory

00:14:26.240 --> 00:14:29.598
holds a lot of promise for
understanding many aspects

00:14:29.598 --> 00:14:34.598
of human experience and
of psychiatric disease.

