snippets of information
from second to second.

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:39.430
For example, seeing a frame of a film

00:15:39.430 --> 00:15:42.270
and seeing that over time that
it looks like fluid motion,

00:15:42.270 --> 00:15:45.040
because we can remember
those individual images,

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:49.040
or short-term memory
which allows us to kind of

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:51.560
understand the meaning of a sentence

00:15:51.560 --> 00:15:53.150
because we remember the
first part of the sentence

00:15:53.150 --> 00:15:54.540
to the end of the sentence.

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:56.970
And then we have something
we call long-term memory

00:15:56.970 --> 00:16:00.230
which really gets to our connections

00:16:00.230 --> 00:16:02.590
with a particular point
in time or a place.

00:16:02.590 --> 00:16:04.240
We tend to remember those things

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:05.650
over longer periods of time,

00:16:05.650 --> 00:16:08.210
particularly when we're exposed to those

00:16:08.210 --> 00:16:09.693
same conditions over again.

00:16:11.170 --> 00:16:13.220
That's a conventional way
of thinking about memory

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:14.740
within the social sciences,

00:16:14.740 --> 00:16:18.840
which picks up a lot of its insight from

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:21.130
the biological sciences.

00:16:21.130 --> 00:16:24.680
Today though, I'm gonna
talk about the intertextual

00:16:24.680 --> 00:16:26.050
and meaning making.

00:16:26.050 --> 00:16:28.020
And take a second to read this quote here.

00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:31.730
It actually connects very well with

00:16:31.730 --> 00:16:34.310
something that Brett mentioned
at the very beginning

00:16:34.310 --> 00:16:35.700
about Polly and her work.

00:16:35.700 --> 00:16:36.950
Why don't you take a second to read this,

00:16:36.950 --> 00:16:38.150
and then we'll continue?

00:16:46.750 --> 00:16:49.790
The basic idea here is
that as human beings,

00:16:49.790 --> 00:16:54.690
storytelling is hardwired into who we are.

00:16:54.690 --> 00:16:56.260
We connect with other people,

00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:58.570
we communicate by telling stories,

00:16:58.570 --> 00:17:01.293
and often those stories
involve our memories.

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:06.080
Today I wanna talk about something called

00:17:06.080 --> 00:17:08.800
the circle of culture which,

00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:11.310
in a second, you'll see how
this relates to the idea

00:17:11.310 --> 00:17:13.760
of what I call intertextual memories.

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:17.610
In here we have a circuit
of five important moments

00:17:17.610 --> 00:17:19.130
starting with representation.

00:17:19.130 --> 00:17:23.130
And by representation, I
mean the irresistible images,

00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:25.420
ideas, utterances,

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:28.440
that shape the way we
think about the world.

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:31.930
And examples of representations
might be things like

00:17:31.930 --> 00:17:36.930
race, a concept that defines
people to certain categories.

00:17:37.240 --> 00:17:38.900
In sociology, we talk about it

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:42.540
as a social constructed concept.

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:44.330
Or gender,

00:17:44.330 --> 00:17:47.930
or any number of other
concepts that are used

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:51.060
to put people into categories
to help us make sense

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:53.513
of what would otherwise
would be a chaotic world.

00:17:54.840 --> 00:17:57.600
The insight of this
particular diagram is that

00:17:57.600 --> 00:17:59.870
representations connected
to all these other things

00:17:59.870 --> 00:18:02.770
like identity, who we are, who we aren't,

00:18:02.770 --> 00:18:04.090
who we hope to be.

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:06.970
Production, the types of
things we produce in society,

00:18:06.970 --> 00:18:09.210
the way we produce them as a reflection

00:18:09.210 --> 00:18:10.620
of who we think we are,

00:18:10.620 --> 00:18:13.840
or of the representations
that order our society.

00:18:13.840 --> 00:18:15.163
The things we consume.

00:18:16.440 --> 00:18:17.810
Advertising, obviously.

00:18:17.810 --> 00:18:19.830
I think Kelsey was sort
of referencing this

00:18:19.830 --> 00:18:21.670
a few minutes ago, in
terms of representation,

00:18:21.670 --> 00:18:24.100
I mean, I'm sorry, repetition
and remembering things.

00:18:24.100 --> 00:18:28.830
One of the core, I guess,
practices within advertising

00:18:28.830 --> 00:18:33.830
is to repeatedly give the same
message over and over again

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:36.260
to compel people to remember the product

00:18:36.260 --> 00:18:38.850
and to hopefully consume it over time.

00:18:38.850 --> 00:18:41.600
And then regulation,
how we draw boundaries

00:18:41.600 --> 00:18:42.480
between different groups,

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:44.510
who's inside, who's outside.

00:18:44.510 --> 00:18:45.900
All of these things are bound up

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:47.910
with the concept of representation,

00:18:47.910 --> 00:18:50.560
they affect who we are
in terms of our identity,

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:53.593
what we as a culture
produce, and what we consume.

00:18:55.290 --> 00:18:57.480
Now, I wanna move forward to what I call

00:18:57.480 --> 00:18:59.810
the media experience.

00:18:59.810 --> 00:19:02.570
And here of course representation becomes

00:19:02.570 --> 00:19:05.470
a very important part
of what happens when we

00:19:05.470 --> 00:19:10.470
experience media text,
movies, television, et cetera.

00:19:10.710 --> 00:19:13.460
Representations like race, like gender

00:19:14.480 --> 00:19:17.590
information the intertextual memories

00:19:17.590 --> 00:19:19.790
that we bring to the media experience.

00:19:19.790 --> 00:19:21.250
When we watch something on television,

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:23.120
we don't watch it cold.

00:19:23.120 --> 00:19:25.270
We're always watching it in relation

00:19:25.270 --> 00:19:27.650
to other things we've seen in the past.

00:19:27.650 --> 00:19:30.250
These media text both shape

00:19:30.250 --> 00:19:31.820
and are shaped by representation.

00:19:31.820 --> 00:19:34.620
That is to say people
who create media text

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:36.850
are trafficking in the representations

00:19:36.850 --> 00:19:39.040
that circulate in society.

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:42.450
Those media text become part of

00:19:42.450 --> 00:19:45.300
the fluid reservoir of
memories that circulate

00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:47.110
as people engage with them.

00:19:47.110 --> 00:19:50.120
This is kinda happening at
the macro level in society,

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:52.570
kinda the level above the individual,

00:19:52.570 --> 00:19:54.300
the level of collectivities.

00:19:54.300 --> 00:19:55.657
If we move more to the micro level

00:19:55.657 --> 00:19:58.380
and what's happening with
individuals like you and me,

00:19:58.380 --> 00:20:00.280
like those of us sitting in this room,

00:20:01.290 --> 00:20:05.580
we are decoding what we're
seeing and hearing on television.

00:20:05.580 --> 00:20:09.510
And often that decoding is a product

00:20:09.510 --> 00:20:13.040
largely of the memories we
bring to that situation.

00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:15.280
We may have encountered
things like this in the past,

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:18.850
which cause us to interpret
it in a particular way.

00:20:18.850 --> 00:20:23.030
At the same time, as
individuals, we exist in society.

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:24.220
We're not isolated.

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:26.830
That is to say we interact
with other people.

00:20:26.830 --> 00:20:30.780
So there's always decoding
in a social context,

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:34.330
often in the networks in which
we are embedded in society,

00:20:34.330 --> 00:20:37.270
our friends, our family, et cetera.

00:20:37.270 --> 00:20:39.810
Often our discussions with them,

00:20:39.810 --> 00:20:42.340
their interpretations of what we saw

00:20:42.340 --> 00:20:45.550
inflect the way we interpret it.

00:20:45.550 --> 00:20:48.130
This goes to what we
call negotiated decoding

00:20:48.130 --> 00:20:50.310
where we kind of negotiate the meaning

00:20:50.310 --> 00:20:52.530
of a particular encounter

00:20:52.530 --> 00:20:56.080
on the basis of our own
individual predispositions,

00:20:56.080 --> 00:20:57.670
filtered through the lens

00:20:57.670 --> 00:21:00.100
of our interactions with important others.

00:21:00.100 --> 00:21:02.470
And as you can see,
this flows back into our

00:21:02.470 --> 00:21:05.430
intertextual memories,
the cycle repeats itself.

00:21:05.430 --> 00:21:06.730
There really is on start or end.

00:21:06.730 --> 00:21:08.530
This is an ongoing cycle.

00:21:08.530 --> 00:21:10.340
Alright, this is a theoretical model

00:21:10.340 --> 00:21:12.580
that's influenced by something known as

00:21:12.580 --> 00:21:14.640
British cultural studies,

00:21:14.640 --> 00:21:16.720
which was an intellectual tradition

00:21:16.720 --> 00:21:19.660
that arose in the 1970s,

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:22.890
largely as a correction to, at the time,

00:21:22.890 --> 00:21:26.470
overly deterministic ways of

00:21:26.470 --> 00:21:29.930
sort of conceptualizing
the relationship between

00:21:29.930 --> 00:21:32.090
meaning making and messages.

00:21:32.090 --> 00:21:33.750
There was a belief at one point in time

00:21:33.750 --> 00:21:34.840
in the magic bullet theory

00:21:34.840 --> 00:21:36.850
that if you send a message,

00:21:36.850 --> 00:21:41.080
it will, like a magic
bullet, enter into our brains

00:21:41.080 --> 00:21:43.960
and lead to a particular type of meaning.

00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:47.200
And that was the
orthodoxy for a long time.

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:49.610
Eventually, however, empirical studies

00:21:49.610 --> 00:21:52.300
started to show that it
doesn't quite work that way.

00:21:52.300 --> 00:21:56.262
People are amazingly creative at

00:21:56.262 --> 00:21:59.710
changing sort of the main
stream or dominant view

00:21:59.710 --> 00:22:01.180
of a particular message.

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:02.360
And so the question became,

00:22:02.360 --> 00:22:03.510
how do we measure this?

00:22:03.510 --> 00:22:05.520
How do we understand this empirically?

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:08.320
And so this model is
meant to try to do this.

00:22:08.320 --> 00:22:10.390
The thing I want to emphasize
today of course is that

00:22:10.390 --> 00:22:11.500
intertextual memories,

00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:13.670
the memories of all the other encounters

00:22:13.670 --> 00:22:14.620
we have in our lives,

00:22:14.620 --> 00:22:18.040
with media, with messages,
with other people

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.223
are an integral part of the process.

00:22:21.720 --> 00:22:24.610
So, to kinda work through
this idea really quickly,

00:22:24.610 --> 00:22:29.180
I wanna take the case of the
1992 Los Angeles uprisings,

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:30.860
something I've written about in the past.

00:22:30.860 --> 00:22:32.730
In fact, I think you reviewed

00:22:32.730 --> 00:22:35.793
a chapter from the book I wrote on this.

00:22:37.160 --> 00:22:42.160
So, one way of thinking
about the 1992 uprisings,

00:22:42.730 --> 00:22:45.600
particularly memories
of the 1992 uprisings

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:48.270
is by looking at the way those events

00:22:48.270 --> 00:22:50.763
were depicted on television.

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:54.113
For those who weren't around in 1992,

00:22:55.270 --> 00:22:57.480
the 1992 uprisings, at the time,

00:22:57.480 --> 00:22:59.900
were described by the LA Times as

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:02.593
the worst riots of the century.

00:23:04.220 --> 00:23:05.560
There was over a billion dollars

00:23:05.560 --> 00:23:08.220
worth of damage in Los Angeles.

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:10.420
There were 52 people who were killed.

00:23:10.420 --> 00:23:11.920
There were thousands arrested.

00:23:13.220 --> 00:23:16.800
The event came on the heels
of not guilty verdicts

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:18.320
in the Rodney King beating case.

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:21.440
He was a black motorist who
was pulled over by police.

00:23:21.440 --> 00:23:25.070
And it just so happen that a passerby

00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:27.653
has camcorder and
recorded the whole thing.

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:31.590
The video was taken to
a local news station

00:23:31.590 --> 00:23:32.763
and it went viral.

00:23:35.528 --> 00:23:37.557
The thing I wanna emphasize here,

00:23:37.557 --> 00:23:40.410
and we can talk more about
this in our discussion,

00:23:40.410 --> 00:23:45.410
is that I screen for 15 groups of viewers

00:23:46.850 --> 00:23:50.870
on the basis of their race and their class

00:23:50.870 --> 00:23:54.150
the exact same 17-minute news clip.

00:23:54.150 --> 00:23:56.310
And part of what I
wanted to understand was

00:23:56.310 --> 00:23:59.070
how are people making
sense of this news clip

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:02.253
based on their positioning in society.

00:24:03.220 --> 00:24:04.910
One of the things I expected

00:24:04.910 --> 00:24:07.670
and one of the things I found was that

00:24:07.670 --> 00:24:11.890
as they talk about the
event in their groups,

00:24:11.890 --> 00:24:16.700
intertextual memories
of other similar events

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:20.890
of movies they had seen, television shows,

00:24:20.890 --> 00:24:23.180
speeches they had heard

00:24:23.180 --> 00:24:26.200
shaped the way they were
processing the information.

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:29.140
And there was interesting
patterning along racial lines,

00:24:29.140 --> 00:24:31.907
in terms of how those
interpretations played out.

00:24:39.100 --> 00:24:41.110
So, in closing, and we can continue this

00:24:41.110 --> 00:24:44.540
a little bit, in a few
minutes, the actual.

00:24:44.540 --> 00:24:47.290
I'll share with you some of
the quotes from the groups.

00:24:48.910 --> 00:24:50.700
The way we see things

00:24:50.700 --> 00:24:54.743
is affected by what we know or believe.

00:24:55.990 --> 00:24:59.090
This is important idea

00:24:59.090 --> 00:25:01.460
that was put forward in the early 1970s

00:25:01.460 --> 00:25:06.360
as part of this tradition from
a book called Ways of Seeing,

00:25:06.360 --> 00:25:09.840
that talked about the subjective nature

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:13.250
of the way we experience
the social worlds around us,

00:25:13.250 --> 00:25:17.050
that it's not purely an objective process

00:25:17.050 --> 00:25:20.410
that can be measured uniformly

00:25:20.410 --> 00:25:22.660
across all viewers, all observers.

00:25:22.660 --> 00:25:25.670
In fact, observers bring
different materials

00:25:25.670 --> 00:25:26.540
to those encounters,

00:25:26.540 --> 00:25:28.550
and one of the important things they bring

00:25:28.550 --> 00:25:30.080
is intertextual memory.

00:25:30.080 --> 00:25:31.602
Thank you.

00:25:31.602 --> 00:25:32.435
(audience applauding)

00:25:32.435 --> 00:25:33.393
- Thank you Darnell.

00:25:33.393 --> 00:25:34.973
Everybody, Darnell Hunt.

00:25:38.810 --> 00:25:41.583
And our final presentation, Peter Sellars.

00:25:44.755 --> 00:25:47.672
(faintly speaking)

00:26:01.014 --> 00:26:02.870
- We'd be hot now, let's be hot.

00:26:02.870 --> 00:26:03.703
Okay.

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:06.530
Thank you, deeply.

00:26:06.530 --> 00:26:08.110
My goodness.

00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:10.340
I am going to try and go through

00:26:10.340 --> 00:26:14.860
some of the same material but
.by a very circuitous route.

00:26:14.860 --> 00:26:17.960
And forgive me, but part
of my training as an artist

00:26:17.960 --> 00:26:20.610
is that the shortest
distance between two points

00:26:20.610 --> 00:26:22.210
means you didn't learn anything.

00:26:23.910 --> 00:26:27.340
And so, for me, the long way around

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:29.880
is actually how life works,

00:26:29.880 --> 00:26:33.800
and what's not immediately
adjacent turns out to be,

00:26:33.800 --> 00:26:36.373
in fact, incredible close.

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:41.670
That question where near
becomes and far becomes near

00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:43.470
is one of the main points of memory.

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:49.620
And I would like to pick
up on several things.

00:26:50.130 --> 00:26:52.120
First of all, I want to thank Brett

00:26:52.120 --> 00:26:53.590
for making these evening.

00:26:53.590 --> 00:26:55.300
I'm so happy to meet these two people

00:26:55.300 --> 00:26:56.490
that I would not have known.

00:26:56.490 --> 00:26:58.210
I've been teaching at UCLA for 30 years.

00:26:58.210 --> 00:26:59.870
Hello, finally I'm meeting you tonight.

00:26:59.870 --> 00:27:00.703
Thank you.

00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:04.223
Thank you very much.

00:27:07.070 --> 00:27:10.490
Just to say, for me, the moral

00:27:11.410 --> 00:27:14.040
questions of memory are really profound,

00:27:14.040 --> 00:27:16.870
and I wanna deal with what we remember,

00:27:16.870 --> 00:27:18.813
what we actually deny,

00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:21.870
what we hold and cherish,

00:27:21.870 --> 00:27:23.250
and what we can't deal with,

00:27:23.250 --> 00:27:24.600
and how we don't deal with,

00:27:25.630 --> 00:27:28.123
and how memory operates
as an ethical system,

00:27:29.150 --> 00:27:31.160
and what memory actually has to be

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:34.660
with the way you decide to live your life,

00:27:34.660 --> 00:27:38.100
which is two words that
are very important to me

00:27:38.100 --> 00:27:41.690
as a performer and somebody
who organizes performance,

00:27:41.690 --> 00:27:42.523
remember

00:27:44.990 --> 00:27:45.823
and repentance.

00:27:49.540 --> 00:27:51.240
What we do in performance

00:27:52.340 --> 00:27:56.120
is we take the voice of
those who are no longer here,

00:27:56.120 --> 00:27:59.447
and we give them new bodies, our own.

00:28:01.230 --> 00:28:03.990
And we invite other people

00:28:03.990 --> 00:28:05.870
to speak through us.

00:28:05.870 --> 00:28:08.180
We create a spirit possession.

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:11.790
We create a moment in which our identity

00:28:11.790 --> 00:28:14.363
is suddenly blurred with another identity.

00:28:15.820 --> 00:28:17.820
And what I want to just mention tonight

00:28:18.870 --> 00:28:22.130
is a performance that I've just come from

00:28:22.130 --> 00:28:23.130
putting on in Madrid.

00:28:23.130 --> 00:28:25.210
It's still running for the next two weeks,

00:28:25.210 --> 00:28:26.660
anyone who's going to Madrid.

00:28:29.621 --> 00:28:31.870
Of two Japanese Noh plays,

00:28:31.870 --> 00:28:35.383
14th century Buddhist, Zen Buddhist plays.

00:28:36.530 --> 00:28:39.370
And we've titled the evening

00:28:40.600 --> 00:28:42.370
one of the lines from one of the plays,

00:28:42.370 --> 00:28:46.083
which is Only the Sound Remains.

00:28:49.010 --> 00:28:50.760
What it means when you lose someone

00:28:52.480 --> 00:28:55.173
but you're remembering them all day,

00:28:56.530 --> 00:28:57.363
all night,

00:28:59.170 --> 00:29:01.523
and you're still in
conversation with them.

00:29:03.470 --> 00:29:05.100
Their physical presence is gone,

00:29:05.100 --> 00:29:06.500
but their voice is with you,

00:29:07.910 --> 00:29:10.293
and only the sound remains.

00:29:13.072 --> 00:29:15.293
In the way in which sound carries memory,

00:29:17.010 --> 00:29:20.163
the way in which a piece
of music carries memory,

00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:24.640
the way in which our
soundtrack all day long

00:29:24.640 --> 00:29:27.723
is actually the way we're
ordering our memories.

00:29:29.500 --> 00:29:31.760
And sound exactly because of it's fluidity

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:34.103
and because of its non-material nature.

00:29:35.630 --> 00:29:39.923
The way it eludes any
attempt to organize it,

00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:44.003
the way voices flow
through your consciousness,

00:29:46.080 --> 00:29:48.343
who you still keep thinking of,

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:54.280
and how that operates of course
in spiritual path because

00:29:54.280 --> 00:29:56.520
Jesus, and Buddha, and Muhammad

00:29:59.270 --> 00:30:00.103
are not here,

00:30:01.700 --> 00:30:04.523
but their voice remains with us.

00:30:08.490 --> 00:30:11.140
And then what it means to remember,

00:30:11.140 --> 00:30:16.140
that is to say Jesus is asking
