00:37:10.710 --> 00:37:13.340
and she was killed at this spot,

00:37:13.340 --> 00:37:15.640
and the person who killed
her was her husband.

00:37:19.630 --> 00:37:21.243
And that was 700 years ago.

00:37:23.710 --> 00:37:26.533
And that is the person
raking leaves here today,

00:37:27.520 --> 00:37:32.373
because the spirit is trapped
here in this place forever.

00:37:36.410 --> 00:37:38.253
And then the spirit disappears.

00:37:43.900 --> 00:37:48.220
And the quality of understanding

00:37:48.220 --> 00:37:50.160
that not only do human
beings have a memory,

00:37:50.160 --> 00:37:52.023
but places have memories,

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:57.000
and that trauma, or moments of
exceptional beauty in a place

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:01.580
live on through the people
who live in that place,

00:38:01.580 --> 00:38:03.510
and that trauma is not over with

00:38:03.510 --> 00:38:05.290
at one historical moment,

00:38:05.290 --> 00:38:07.670
but actually across centuries.

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:11.080
That trauma repeats itself and affects

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:12.793
people in a certain place.

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:17.210
And also moments of beauty

00:38:18.170 --> 00:38:19.243
and moments of truth.

00:38:21.830 --> 00:38:24.120
So, the play that I'm

00:38:26.080 --> 00:38:31.080
dealing with is called
Tsunemasa in Japanese,

00:38:32.150 --> 00:38:35.780
and it's a priest who makes a ceremony

00:38:35.780 --> 00:38:38.640
for a young man who died in battle,

00:38:38.640 --> 00:38:40.440
because this young man killed someone

00:38:40.440 --> 00:38:41.713
and then was killed.

00:38:43.570 --> 00:38:46.393
