00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:53.430
that we don't really forget,

00:47:53.430 --> 00:47:55.700
that we think we forget,

00:47:55.700 --> 00:47:58.490
but there are these
memories that are present

00:47:58.490 --> 00:48:01.263
that will come out, and that
we're not even aware of.

00:48:02.120 --> 00:48:03.680
There's something called inhibition

00:48:03.680 --> 00:48:06.170
that gets placed on top of those memories.

00:48:06.170 --> 00:48:07.680
And then in a certain situation,

00:48:07.680 --> 00:48:11.180
that might come away,
and it's actually there.

00:48:11.180 --> 00:48:12.910
So I like to just talk for a moment about

00:48:12.910 --> 00:48:14.460
forgetting and what that means.

00:48:15.680 --> 00:48:18.000
- That's an interesting question.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:19.910
When I was conducting the study

00:48:19.910 --> 00:48:22.833
that I referred briefly a few moments ago,

00:48:24.190 --> 00:48:27.140
one of the things I was
trying to explore was

00:48:27.140 --> 00:48:30.310
sort of how when people
get together in a group

00:48:30.310 --> 00:48:34.340
they collectively negotiate
the meaning of something.

00:48:34.340 --> 00:48:37.190
And one of the theories

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:39.380
called informational influence is that

00:48:40.400 --> 00:48:43.020
when you're in a group and there's kind of

00:48:45.710 --> 00:48:48.610
a dominant understanding of something,

00:48:48.610 --> 00:48:51.250
the question is what happens
when the group discusses it.

00:48:51.250 --> 00:48:54.000
Well, there's something
called group polarization

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:56.670
where the view can even
become more dominant over time

00:48:56.670 --> 00:48:59.680
as people are reinforcing
one another's understandings.

00:48:59.680 --> 00:49:03.360
And one of the arguments
for how that happens

00:49:03.360 --> 00:49:06.130
is something called informational
influence theory that,

00:49:06.130 --> 00:49:07.470
people who come to the group

00:49:07.470 --> 00:49:09.470
with a predisposition towards seeing

00:49:09.470 --> 00:49:11.290
something in a certain way

00:49:11.290 --> 00:49:14.300
may have forgotten some of the arguments

00:49:14.300 --> 00:49:15.550
to support that position.

00:49:15.550 --> 00:49:17.577
But when they get around
people like themselves,

00:49:17.577 --> 00:49:19.940
and they hear that information again,

00:49:19.940 --> 00:49:21.810
they're like, "Aha, that's right."

00:49:21.810 --> 00:49:24.220
And they actually harden their

00:49:24.220 --> 00:49:25.740
adherence to that point of view.

00:49:25.740 --> 00:49:27.830
So this is something that I actually found

00:49:27.830 --> 00:49:29.280
in all the groups I study.

00:49:29.280 --> 00:49:31.510
Most of the groups, if you sort of

00:49:32.430 --> 00:49:34.910
did this quasi experimental
thing where you measured

00:49:34.910 --> 00:49:36.620
kind of where they were on a scale

00:49:36.620 --> 00:49:38.520
when they first came to the meeting,

00:49:38.520 --> 00:49:40.260
by the end, they're way over here.

00:49:40.260 --> 00:49:41.370
And this was true in every group,

00:49:41.370 --> 00:49:43.430
and the scales will go
in different directions,

00:49:43.430 --> 00:49:47.170
depending upon the basic
understanding of the group.

00:49:47.170 --> 00:49:48.940
And so forgetting was a big part of that,

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:50.690
and then remembering,
once it was brought up

00:49:50.690 --> 00:49:51.790
in group conversation.

