01:01:27.180 --> 01:01:30.410
but I was curious about
we live in a time where

01:01:30.410 --> 01:01:32.250
information is mass produced

01:01:32.250 --> 01:01:34.720
and mitigated on an unprecedented scale

01:01:34.720 --> 01:01:37.760
through social media and the internet.

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:38.593
And so in some ways,

01:01:38.593 --> 01:01:40.810
we have so much more access

01:01:40.810 --> 01:01:43.853
to different kinds of collective
memory or personal memory.

01:01:44.820 --> 01:01:47.870
But I feel like that
mitigation also impacts

01:01:47.870 --> 01:01:50.690
what we were discussing
about the culture circuit

01:01:50.690 --> 01:01:51.857
and intertextual memory.

01:01:51.857 --> 01:01:53.730
And so how do we facilitate

01:01:54.590 --> 01:01:56.660
more of those conversation
where people come together

01:01:56.660 --> 01:01:57.740
and they bring their different

01:01:57.740 --> 01:01:59.450
interpretations of events.

01:01:59.450 --> 01:02:01.820
And instead of being polarized or hardened

01:02:01.820 --> 01:02:04.483
into their former belief, they are,

01:02:05.550 --> 01:02:08.300
that plasticity is encouraged.

01:02:08.300 --> 01:02:09.200
And I guess I was just wandering

01:02:09.200 --> 01:02:11.397
what all of your perspectives on that are.

01:02:12.520 --> 01:02:15.220
- Well, maybe I'll take
the first stab at that.

01:02:15.220 --> 01:02:17.130
That's a great question.

01:02:17.130 --> 01:02:22.130
I think one of the reason why
when I was asked to do this

01:02:22.210 --> 01:02:24.170
that I picked this particular example

01:02:24.170 --> 01:02:26.330
is because I mean it's an old example.

01:02:26.330 --> 01:02:28.880
It comes from 25 years ago.

01:02:28.880 --> 01:02:32.570
But for me, it really
speaks to the present moment

01:02:32.570 --> 01:02:37.570
in terms of the siloization
of our culture in many ways,

01:02:38.100 --> 01:02:40.910
the ways in which mini groups

01:02:40.910 --> 01:02:42.330
who are living in these echo chambers

01:02:42.330 --> 01:02:46.560
where they're only hearing
ideas and thoughts that

01:02:46.560 --> 01:02:48.520
reinforce their predispositions,

01:02:48.520 --> 01:02:50.510
and there aren't as many opportunities

01:02:50.510 --> 01:02:52.230
for us to kinda come together,

01:02:52.230 --> 01:02:54.010
or rather technology has allowed us

01:02:54.010 --> 01:02:55.370
to avoid having to come together.

01:02:55.370 --> 01:02:56.390
I guess that's the better way to put it.

01:02:56.390 --> 01:02:57.750
I mean there are opportunities
to come together,

01:02:57.750 --> 01:03:00.320
but it's easier not to do that.

01:03:00.320 --> 01:03:03.600
And I think it leads to the
type of polarization we see.

01:03:03.600 --> 01:03:04.800
We see it in small groups,

01:03:04.800 --> 01:03:08.430
and that's what I was able
to show in the study I did,

01:03:08.430 --> 01:03:12.160
this whole phenomenon of
small group polarization

01:03:12.160 --> 01:03:14.190
based on all these mechanism
that we talked about,

01:03:14.190 --> 01:03:16.860
like selectively forgetting
and then remembering,

01:03:16.860 --> 01:03:17.693
and "Oh, that's right.

01:03:17.693 --> 01:03:20.367
"Well, now I'm gonna
be even more staunched

01:03:20.367 --> 01:03:21.717
"in this particular idea."

01:03:24.810 --> 01:03:27.430
I think it really is about

01:03:27.430 --> 01:03:31.550
finding ways to make our
communities more inclusive

01:03:31.550 --> 01:03:33.540
and bringing more people into the tent

01:03:33.540 --> 01:03:37.610
and having conversations
that cross the boundaries

01:03:37.610 --> 01:03:40.580
that social media has allowed us

01:03:41.645 --> 01:03:45.720
to erect in very regular
and patterned ways.

01:03:47.790 --> 01:03:51.320
- [Audience Member] Thank you.

01:03:51.320 --> 01:03:53.220
- There are a couple
ways I think about this,

01:03:53.220 --> 01:03:55.400
and part of the way I'm framing it is,

01:03:55.400 --> 01:03:57.870
again, to come back in
my discipline in a way,

01:03:57.870 --> 01:04:01.050
which is that...

01:04:01.050 --> 01:04:04.920
Two things, one is I think I'm aware that

01:04:04.920 --> 01:04:09.680
fear really changes the
way we process information

01:04:09.680 --> 01:04:14.520
has incredibly profound impact on how we

01:04:16.440 --> 01:04:19.280
perceive things and
how we remember things.

01:04:19.280 --> 01:04:20.980
And so I think that there's a need

01:04:20.980 --> 01:04:23.970
to really be very
cognizant of how much fear

01:04:23.970 --> 01:04:26.853
is driving the information
that's coming in.

01:04:27.860 --> 01:04:29.990
And then the other part is that

01:04:29.990 --> 01:04:32.830
I think there's a real need to recognize

01:04:32.830 --> 01:04:36.040
when I was talking about how
early childhood experience

01:04:37.074 --> 01:04:39.783
is this critical period
for shaping the brain.

01:04:41.360 --> 01:04:43.060
There are really profound studies

01:04:43.060 --> 01:04:46.150
that show, for example,
that learning languages

01:04:46.150 --> 01:04:48.840
when you're very young,
in the first year of life,

01:04:48.840 --> 01:04:50.040
you're not learning the language,

01:04:50.040 --> 01:04:52.113
but you're hearing, for example,

01:04:53.540 --> 01:04:55.893
a language that has different tones.

01:04:57.580 --> 01:05:00.350
If you don't hear that in
your first year of life,

01:05:00.350 --> 01:05:04.160
you can't even those
distinctions later in your life.

01:05:04.160 --> 01:05:07.390
So it really shapes the
way you perceive the world.

01:05:07.390 --> 01:05:10.443
And I think that there's
a reality to that,

01:05:11.360 --> 01:05:14.740
to recognize that our brains
have been wired in a way

01:05:14.740 --> 01:05:18.480
that we see things through the lens

01:05:20.153 --> 01:05:22.040
of the people we've been around.

01:05:22.040 --> 01:05:24.340
That to me is a little bit liberating

01:05:24.340 --> 01:05:27.970
in the sense that if that were recognized,

01:05:27.970 --> 01:05:32.487
there might be more of
a openness to saying,

01:05:32.487 --> 01:05:36.160
"I'm seeing things
incredibly subjectively."

01:05:38.290 --> 01:05:39.320
And to go back to you,

01:05:39.320 --> 01:05:41.610
we're talking about zen traditions.

01:05:41.610 --> 01:05:45.193
There's this tradition of
zen mind, beginner's mind.

01:05:46.400 --> 01:05:49.090
If your mind is always
being changed by experience,

01:05:49.090 --> 01:05:50.840
there's no really beginner's mind,

01:05:50.840 --> 01:05:53.740
but you can at least
try to get towards that

01:05:53.740 --> 01:05:56.190
where you recognize that your experience

01:05:56.190 --> 01:05:58.833
are really shaping how
you perceive the world.

01:06:01.040 --> 01:06:03.350
- Just to go one step, next step,

01:06:03.350 --> 01:06:07.720
which is of course that
emptiness, that beginner's mind,

01:06:07.720 --> 01:06:12.680
that understanding that
everything is empty actually.

01:06:12.680 --> 01:06:15.470
And emptying it of all the associations,

01:06:15.470 --> 01:06:18.350
all the meanings, and really beginning

01:06:19.730 --> 01:06:21.340
to try and find

01:06:21.340 --> 01:06:23.090
the place at which things are empty

01:06:24.230 --> 01:06:27.260
is very, very, very powerful thing to do.

01:06:27.260 --> 01:06:29.990
And a simple thing, for example,

01:06:29.990 --> 01:06:31.593
just working in theater,

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:36.000
is, for me, whenever I'm
putting something on stage,

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:40.293
I have to make sure the actor
is playing the opposite.

01:06:42.660 --> 01:06:43.950
In Japanese Noh drama,

01:06:43.950 --> 01:06:48.123
it says if you're going to
be an angry person on stage,

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:51.070
you have to be very quiet,

01:06:51.070 --> 01:06:53.843
and very balanced, and
very self-possessed.

01:06:54.750 --> 01:06:55.860
It would be incorrect

01:06:55.860 --> 01:06:57.913
to show an angry person out of control.

01:07:01.104 --> 01:07:04.530
You always have to put
a little of the opposite

01:07:04.530 --> 01:07:06.710
to make sure the truth is there.

01:07:06.710 --> 01:07:08.110
And that's one of the things as art,

01:07:08.110 --> 01:07:08.943
we're always dealing

01:07:08.943 --> 01:07:10.560
with the difference
between art and propaganda.

01:07:10.560 --> 01:07:12.890
Propaganda is trying to
convince you of something,

01:07:12.890 --> 01:07:15.720
and therefore it's telling
one side of the story.

01:07:15.720 --> 01:07:19.980
So, what we always want to do
on stage is the shy person,

01:07:19.980 --> 01:07:23.310
if you have an actor
act like a little mouse,

01:07:23.310 --> 01:07:25.030
it's ridiculous.

01:07:25.030 --> 01:07:28.500
The shy person is probably the
loudest person in the room.

01:07:28.500 --> 01:07:30.630
And so you always have a dramatic choice

01:07:30.630 --> 01:07:33.240
that's the opposite of the obvious choice,

01:07:33.240 --> 01:07:35.470
and you make sure that
you're balancing everything

01:07:35.470 --> 01:07:36.680
with its opposite,

01:07:36.680 --> 01:07:39.993
because everything has to
contain its opposite to be true.

01:07:41.440 --> 01:07:44.890
And that begins to create
some sense of balance,

01:07:44.890 --> 01:07:46.940
some sense of equilibrium.

01:07:46.940 --> 01:07:49.460
And for the actor, it gives them something

01:07:49.460 --> 01:07:51.830
or her something to play against

01:07:51.830 --> 01:07:53.580
that actually creates a depth,

01:07:53.580 --> 01:07:57.390
and creates a complexity
of emotional experience.

01:07:57.390 --> 01:08:00.610
And you're never doing a one for one

01:08:00.610 --> 01:08:02.340
obvious correlation,

01:08:02.340 --> 01:08:04.640
but you make everybody have to go

01:08:04.640 --> 01:08:05.980
through the opposite of what it is

01:08:05.980 --> 01:08:08.220
they're supposedly expressing.

01:08:08.220 --> 01:08:11.620
And that creates something
like the complexity

01:08:11.620 --> 01:08:12.770
of human consciousness.

01:08:19.370 --> 01:08:20.720
- All the way up on the right side there,

01:08:20.720 --> 01:08:21.853
I see a hand up.

01:08:25.130 --> 01:08:27.810
- I'm wondering if certain issues

01:08:27.810 --> 01:08:30.670
that we're facing in terms
of memory and attention

01:08:30.670 --> 01:08:34.170
are helping to increase our sense of

01:08:34.170 --> 01:08:36.860
tribalism and also our

01:08:38.030 --> 01:08:39.620
sense of...

01:08:41.798 --> 01:08:42.990
How would I say this?

01:08:42.990 --> 01:08:46.490
Very easily instigated outrage.

01:08:46.490 --> 01:08:48.880
For instance, some of my professors,

01:08:48.880 --> 01:08:52.320
when I was here as a student
in the English lit department

01:08:52.320 --> 01:08:53.630
spoke of people

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:59.773
reciting Homer's entire works from memory.

01:09:01.340 --> 01:09:04.140
When I was growing up, pre-digital age,

01:09:04.140 --> 01:09:07.280
I had 100 phone numbers in my head.

01:09:07.280 --> 01:09:09.520
Now I can barely remember
my own phone number

01:09:09.520 --> 01:09:10.620
to give out to people.

01:09:11.770 --> 01:09:14.480
Also, there's a lot of issue
with the tension I think.

01:09:14.480 --> 01:09:16.640
There's a lot of, correct me if I'm wrong,

01:09:16.640 --> 01:09:19.450
a lot of neuro biological
studies out right now

01:09:19.450 --> 01:09:22.010
that attention is rapidly changing.

01:09:22.010 --> 01:09:24.560
People's attention
spans are quite shorter.

01:09:24.560 --> 01:09:26.693
I'm wondering if these two issues,

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:31.330
memory which we're relying on
our devices for all the time,

01:09:31.330 --> 01:09:33.490
why remember anything
when you can look it up,

01:09:33.490 --> 01:09:35.620
and also diminished attention

01:09:35.620 --> 01:09:39.553
are contributing to these other
issues we're talking about.

01:09:45.560 --> 01:09:46.810
- I would agree with that,

01:09:46.810 --> 01:09:49.290
and I think part of the issues is that

01:09:49.290 --> 01:09:52.390
those technologies are evolving

01:09:52.390 --> 01:09:55.200
a lot more quickly than
our brains are evolving.

01:09:55.200 --> 01:09:56.523
And I think that,

01:10:00.070 --> 01:10:01.143
a couple things,

01:10:02.360 --> 01:10:04.820
it's important to realize that we don't,

01:10:04.820 --> 01:10:06.850
our brain, when we perceive things,

01:10:06.850 --> 01:10:09.360
we actually are making
up half of what we see.

01:10:09.360 --> 01:10:10.850
If you figure out what

01:10:10.850 --> 01:10:13.300
is coming into your retina
and what you're looking at,

01:10:13.300 --> 01:10:14.990
we're making up half of it,

01:10:14.990 --> 01:10:17.550
but there's so much
stuff coming in right now

01:10:17.550 --> 01:10:19.440
that I do think it is...

01:10:21.100 --> 01:10:23.630
Maybe there just isn't the time to really

01:10:23.630 --> 01:10:27.393
put everything together in a
way that's very thoughtful.

01:10:28.510 --> 01:10:33.510
I remember my daughter
in high school took a

01:10:33.740 --> 01:10:34.840
poetry class,

01:10:34.840 --> 01:10:37.553
and the English teacher, when I asked him,

01:10:38.470 --> 01:10:41.820
why having a whole
semester just on poetry.

01:10:41.820 --> 01:10:42.930
I was delighted,

01:10:42.930 --> 01:10:45.560
but he was very explicit about it,

01:10:45.560 --> 01:10:46.760
and he said it's because

01:10:47.721 --> 01:10:51.740
it's so important if
you're 15, 16 years old

01:10:51.740 --> 01:10:55.063
to have to take time to read a poem,

01:10:56.280 --> 01:10:57.920
really read a poem carefully

01:10:57.920 --> 01:10:59.830
and spend your time reading the poem.

01:10:59.830 --> 01:11:04.830
And it made me realize
how rarely that happens.

01:11:06.610 --> 01:11:07.820
I grew up with that,

01:11:07.820 --> 01:11:12.820
but I certainly feel that
my children, my students,

01:11:12.920 --> 01:11:15.240
they don't have as much time.

01:11:15.240 --> 01:11:17.730
And at the medical school,
I can tell you that

01:11:17.730 --> 01:11:21.650
as a physician, you are now,

01:11:21.650 --> 01:11:23.490
when you see a patient,

01:11:23.490 --> 01:11:25.910
you look at the patient and
you talk to the patient,

01:11:25.910 --> 01:11:28.210
but you are with the monitor

01:11:28.210 --> 01:11:31.113
that tells you their
entire medical history,

01:11:32.380 --> 01:11:34.930
and some cases their entire imaging data,

01:11:34.930 --> 01:11:37.443
their lab data, their genomic data.

01:11:38.691 --> 01:11:42.230
So I think how we learn how to
process all that information,

01:11:42.230 --> 01:11:44.180
and whether that leads to divisiveness,

01:11:44.180 --> 01:11:48.403
it certain leads to kind of
a sense of being overwhelmed.

01:11:50.941 --> 01:11:53.140
- I think that people

01:11:54.800 --> 01:11:57.760
in the midst of being confronted
with all this information,

01:11:57.760 --> 01:12:00.330
they have to find ways
to quickly organize it,

01:12:00.330 --> 01:12:05.330
which allows us to, rather
prompts us to rely upon

01:12:06.850 --> 01:12:09.480
representations, the concept
that I mentioned earlier,

01:12:09.480 --> 01:12:11.850
which get into these types of divisions

01:12:11.850 --> 01:12:13.850
and constructions and categorizations

01:12:14.890 --> 01:12:16.100
of people and groups

01:12:16.100 --> 01:12:18.800
and the familiar versus
what's not familiar.

01:12:18.800 --> 01:12:20.450
And so, I can see how

01:12:22.030 --> 01:12:23.090
we're trying to play catch up

01:12:23.090 --> 01:12:24.380
in terms of our own development

01:12:24.380 --> 01:12:26.330
in keeping up with these
new technologies that

01:12:26.330 --> 01:12:30.010
we could revert back to some of these more

01:12:30.010 --> 01:12:31.110
comfortable tendencies.

01:12:31.110 --> 01:12:34.084
They, in the long run, I
think are very dangerous.

01:12:34.084 --> 01:12:36.350
- And I think spending time with the texts

01:12:36.350 --> 01:12:38.300
is also like spending time with people.

01:12:40.250 --> 01:12:44.030
What it means in the
history of spirituality

01:12:44.030 --> 01:12:47.523
that most of these texts,
the Bible, the Quran,

01:12:49.020 --> 01:12:52.970
the Buddhist sutras
were never written down

01:12:52.970 --> 01:12:54.780
for several centuries,

01:12:54.780 --> 01:12:57.200
and people learn them by heart.

01:12:57.200 --> 01:13:00.220
And what it is right now
if you're a Tibetan monk

01:13:00.220 --> 01:13:02.820
is you don't have a pile of books.

01:13:02.820 --> 01:13:07.260
You actually have memorized
every one of these texts,

01:13:07.260 --> 01:13:10.070
and what it means to
know something by heart,

01:13:10.070 --> 01:13:12.970
what it means to have
gone through this text

01:13:12.970 --> 01:13:17.970
700 times in one day until you begin to,

01:13:17.970 --> 01:13:20.890
new meanings begin to reveal themselves,

01:13:20.890 --> 01:13:23.420
when it's also one rather
than looking at somebody

01:13:23.420 --> 01:13:26.320
and guessing who they are in one second,

01:13:26.320 --> 01:13:29.230
what it means to spend
quality time with someone

01:13:29.230 --> 01:13:32.580
and learn that all the things
you thought someone was,

01:13:32.580 --> 01:13:34.180
of course they're none of those things,

01:13:34.180 --> 01:13:36.020
which is not just occasionally,

01:13:36.020 --> 01:13:38.720
that's all with everyone you meet.

01:13:38.720 --> 01:13:41.223
You're wrong about almost everything.

01:13:42.130 --> 01:13:44.853
And until you actually
spend time with someone,

01:13:46.070 --> 01:13:47.317
for one thing, they're trying to convince

01:13:47.317 --> 01:13:50.120
you of something that they're not as well.

01:13:50.120 --> 01:13:51.813
I'm not blaming one side.

01:13:53.070 --> 01:13:54.830
But what it takes to spend time

01:13:54.830 --> 01:13:57.550
to get to know who
someone really is behind

01:13:57.550 --> 01:13:59.100
what all those appearances are.

01:14:00.260 --> 01:14:05.090
That's just time, investment
of time and attention.

01:14:05.090 --> 01:14:06.930
And that quality of attention

01:14:06.930 --> 01:14:08.506
can move to how they're dressed

01:14:08.506 --> 01:14:10.790
and the Sherlock Holmes thing

01:14:12.400 --> 01:14:14.560
to a deeper place,

01:14:14.560 --> 01:14:17.600
which is actually the Sufi place

01:14:17.600 --> 01:14:21.010
where you're able to look and listen

01:14:22.090 --> 01:14:24.810
because you're self-focused very deeply.

01:14:24.810 --> 01:14:28.510
One Sufi master who I toured with for

01:14:28.510 --> 01:14:29.760
several years of my life,

01:14:29.760 --> 01:14:31.923
a great Nubian oud player.

01:14:33.200 --> 01:14:35.190
We would be in some crowded restaurant

01:14:35.190 --> 01:14:37.130
in Los Angeles or Berlin,

01:14:37.130 --> 01:14:40.180
and he point to a table on
the other side of the room.

01:14:40.180 --> 01:14:42.317
And he'd say "Okay, Peter,
what are they saying?"

01:14:43.420 --> 01:14:45.447
I would say, "Hamza, this
restaurant is so loud.

01:14:45.447 --> 01:14:47.190
"Everything is so crazy."

01:14:47.190 --> 01:14:48.897
And he said, "You don't listen.

01:14:49.817 --> 01:14:51.837
"You don't know how to listen.

01:14:51.837 --> 01:14:56.740
"Focus on that table and
tell me what they're saying."

01:14:56.740 --> 01:14:58.632
- [Kelsey] That's
eavesdropping, I'm sorry.

01:14:58.632 --> 01:15:00.154
(laughs)

01:15:00.154 --> 01:15:02.670
- Yeah, no, but it's also,

01:15:02.670 --> 01:15:05.320
in the Sufi thing, it's about healing.

01:15:05.320 --> 01:15:06.660
It's about actually

01:15:06.660 --> 01:15:09.400
knowing most human beings
are trying to prevent you

01:15:09.400 --> 01:15:11.560
from understanding who they are,

01:15:11.560 --> 01:15:13.670
and you have to reach inside

01:15:13.670 --> 01:15:15.800
and be able to look in someone's eyes

01:15:15.800 --> 01:15:18.150
and see everything that's
ever happened to them

01:15:19.180 --> 01:15:21.130
in a way that maybe they themselves

01:15:21.130 --> 01:15:24.290
don't even acknowledge or understand.

