01:28:37.680 --> 01:28:40.283
but also heal and move forward?

01:28:45.222 --> 01:28:46.250
- I'm trying to think about that

01:28:46.250 --> 01:28:47.623
in the context of memory.

01:28:50.020 --> 01:28:53.510
Well, I mean, I think healing

01:28:55.640 --> 01:29:00.200
involves confronting trauma
on some very basic levels.

01:29:00.200 --> 01:29:02.800
I mean I think any psychoanalyst
will tell you that.

01:29:03.960 --> 01:29:08.390
Kind of engaging with the memories that

01:29:09.500 --> 01:29:12.280
kinda flow from the trauma

01:29:12.280 --> 01:29:14.750
allows you to bring it in the present

01:29:14.750 --> 01:29:17.440
and to analyze it in ways that

01:29:17.440 --> 01:29:19.660
subconsciously maybe you're not aware of,

01:29:19.660 --> 01:29:21.100
and allows you to kinda,

01:29:21.100 --> 01:29:23.200
again, it must have
some effect in the brain

01:29:23.200 --> 01:29:25.570
in terms of how you think about it

01:29:25.570 --> 01:29:26.803
from that point forward,

01:29:27.920 --> 01:29:32.173
and creates the condition
of possibility to kinda,

01:29:34.420 --> 01:29:36.021
it involves other groups

01:29:36.021 --> 01:29:38.230
to engage with those groups that

01:29:38.230 --> 01:29:40.343
may have been off limits in the past.

01:29:41.210 --> 01:29:42.900
So I think on some very basic level,

01:29:42.900 --> 01:29:44.070
you have to acknowledge

01:29:44.070 --> 01:29:46.070
whatever it was that created the trauma,

01:29:46.070 --> 01:29:49.760
and then bring it into the present,

01:29:49.760 --> 01:29:53.853
analyze it, and talk
about it, communicate.

01:29:54.900 --> 01:29:57.600
Share the stories that are
associated with the trauma.

01:29:58.797 --> 01:29:59.670
- I mean I agree.

01:29:59.670 --> 01:30:04.230
I think you have to attend to the trauma,

01:30:04.230 --> 01:30:06.100
and I do think that there's

01:30:06.100 --> 01:30:08.173
a really important part in,

01:30:11.800 --> 01:30:14.750
for therapy, that there's
another person there,

01:30:14.750 --> 01:30:16.890
that it's actually a social activity.

01:30:16.890 --> 01:30:18.833
It's not just on your own.

01:30:21.920 --> 01:30:24.060
Thinking about it, confronting it,

01:30:24.060 --> 01:30:25.380
but it's acknowledging,

01:30:25.380 --> 01:30:27.340
and I think that's part of story telling.

01:30:27.340 --> 01:30:29.270
It really is a way of being able

01:30:29.270 --> 01:30:30.850
to tell your story to somebody,

01:30:30.850 --> 01:30:34.140
your narrative and have it
understood in a way that's

01:30:35.320 --> 01:30:37.280
accepted as a human experience,

01:30:37.280 --> 01:30:39.320
but not as one that is

01:30:40.490 --> 01:30:42.470
sort of faithful in a way.

01:30:42.470 --> 01:30:46.483
That means that you're
constrained by that faith.

01:30:47.450 --> 01:30:48.590
There certainly are,

01:30:48.590 --> 01:30:50.590
for some things like PTSD,

01:30:50.590 --> 01:30:54.210
there are lots of very
biological approaches

01:30:54.210 --> 01:30:56.800
just trying to increase
the brain plasticity.

01:30:56.800 --> 01:30:58.570
There are a lot of people
who try to do things

01:30:58.570 --> 01:31:02.570
like exposure therapy for a phobia.

01:31:02.570 --> 01:31:05.020
And I would say there it's really

01:31:05.020 --> 01:31:07.610
part of the important thing
is that there's somebody else

01:31:07.610 --> 01:31:11.670
who's there, who's helping
you relive that experience,

01:31:11.670 --> 01:31:13.560
but relive it in a different way,

01:31:13.560 --> 01:31:17.470
because it's not dangerous,

01:31:17.470 --> 01:31:19.320
it's not threatening in the second,

01:31:19.320 --> 01:31:22.363
in the reliving of it.

01:31:23.580 --> 01:31:26.600
- Absolutely, and not to be alone

01:31:26.600 --> 01:31:27.940
is the most important thing,

01:31:27.940 --> 01:31:31.430
because your trauma is
all about being alone,

01:31:31.430 --> 01:31:34.090
and not being able to deal with yourself,

01:31:34.090 --> 01:31:35.490
not being proud of yourself,

01:31:35.490 --> 01:31:36.640
in fact, being ashamed,

01:31:39.760 --> 01:31:41.460
and to realize you're not the only person

01:31:41.460 --> 01:31:42.800
who's going through this.

01:31:42.800 --> 01:31:45.160
So what this means that it's shared,

01:31:45.160 --> 01:31:46.150
that it's shared,

01:31:46.150 --> 01:31:49.687
and again, we're also sure
something is wrong with us

01:31:49.687 --> 01:31:53.080
and we're not dealing with
their systematic things going on

01:31:53.080 --> 01:31:55.150
that are affecting
large numbers of people.

01:31:55.150 --> 01:31:57.730
And when you begin to
realize you're not alone,

01:31:57.730 --> 01:31:59.820
its a very, very deep thing.

01:31:59.820 --> 01:32:02.500
I would just add on
behalf of the arts that

01:32:02.500 --> 01:32:05.320
officially the Canadian government

01:32:05.320 --> 01:32:07.810
is now saying the only treatment

01:32:07.810 --> 01:32:10.750
that can actually be put
forward at the moment

01:32:12.320 --> 01:32:14.013
for PTSD is music.

01:32:15.190 --> 01:32:18.030
And music is being used
over and over again now

01:32:18.030 --> 01:32:22.010
for returning Canadian soldiers
from Afghanistan and Iraq,

01:32:22.010 --> 01:32:25.683
and it's being very,
very powerful results.

01:32:26.830 --> 01:32:30.003
And music has a way of both liberating,

01:32:30.840 --> 01:32:35.710
and relaxing, and opening,
and creating a spaciousness

01:32:35.710 --> 01:32:37.700
of thought and feelings.

01:32:37.700 --> 01:32:39.810
And at the same time, music can deal with

01:32:39.810 --> 01:32:43.216
very, very intense emotional states.

01:32:43.216 --> 01:32:48.140
And so music has had a
profound effect on soldiers

01:32:49.040 --> 01:32:50.733
returning from these last wars.

01:32:53.290 --> 01:32:55.950
- One last question from the audience.

01:32:55.950 --> 01:32:56.900
Do we have a microphone?

01:32:56.900 --> 01:32:57.747
Here we are.

01:32:58.930 --> 01:33:01.560
- You were mentioning longer,

01:33:01.560 --> 01:33:05.863
short-term memory and
long-term memory before.

01:33:07.080 --> 01:33:12.080
So, why when we are very old

01:33:12.172 --> 01:33:15.150
and near the end of our life,

01:33:15.150 --> 01:33:19.360
we remember only things a long time ago

01:33:19.360 --> 01:33:24.360
and we kinda don't want,
deny things that are present?

01:33:24.610 --> 01:33:26.973
I don't know, you call
it short-term memory.

01:33:28.348 --> 01:33:29.993
It's only a long-term memory.

01:33:31.485 --> 01:33:34.610
It's very strange because
I'm thinking about the brain

01:33:34.610 --> 01:33:36.560
that is corroding, that is getting old,

01:33:37.800 --> 01:33:40.700
and actually you should
remember the last things

01:33:40.700 --> 01:33:45.700
you just did, not the things
before because it's gone.

01:33:47.670 --> 01:33:51.130
Instead, when you hear the last word

01:33:51.130 --> 01:33:52.853
of people that almost died,

01:33:54.120 --> 01:33:56.960
tell you things from the past,

01:33:56.960 --> 01:33:59.870
from when they were young.

01:33:59.870 --> 01:34:01.313
They remember the mother,

01:34:02.359 --> 01:34:05.660
they tell you story that are really back,

01:34:05.660 --> 01:34:07.180
and that strike me.

01:34:07.180 --> 01:34:10.420
I would like to know as a scientist

01:34:10.420 --> 01:34:11.920
what's happening to our brain.

01:34:13.354 --> 01:34:14.187
(laughs)

01:34:14.187 --> 01:34:15.570
- Well, I'm gonna,

01:34:15.570 --> 01:34:17.800
Kelsey, this is your area of specialty.

01:34:17.800 --> 01:34:20.230
Is it true that it's all in there,

01:34:20.230 --> 01:34:21.849
it's just a matter of how we access it?

01:34:21.849 --> 01:34:23.450
Is that what it really is?

01:34:23.450 --> 01:34:25.530
How do these things work?

01:34:25.530 --> 01:34:27.990
- Well, I mean--
(audience laughs)

01:34:27.990 --> 01:34:28.823
- It's a good last question.

01:34:28.823 --> 01:34:30.780
- I'll be perfectly honest that

01:34:30.780 --> 01:34:33.240
not only do I not know
how they really work,

01:34:33.240 --> 01:34:35.360
but nobody knows how they really work,

01:34:35.360 --> 01:34:39.800
but I can tell you what
some hypothesis are,

01:34:39.800 --> 01:34:43.617
which is that when I talked
about this brain plasticity

01:34:43.617 --> 01:34:46.363
and about the ability of
forming different synapses,

01:34:47.400 --> 01:34:52.400
that that's really good in young people.

01:34:52.670 --> 01:34:55.250
It's not so good as you get older.

01:34:55.250 --> 01:34:58.580
And so you really have
created these circuits

01:34:58.580 --> 01:35:00.290
that are pretty hardwired,

01:35:00.290 --> 01:35:04.910
and so you could remember
things from a long time ago,

01:35:04.910 --> 01:35:07.210
but it's harder to have that plasticity

01:35:07.210 --> 01:35:10.290
that's gonna encode new memories.

01:35:10.290 --> 01:35:12.243
That's one of the things that,

01:35:13.080 --> 01:35:18.080
to me, that is exactly what
I work on in my own lab,

01:35:18.760 --> 01:35:20.730
is trying to understand what

01:35:20.730 --> 01:35:22.920
at a molecular level is happening

01:35:22.920 --> 01:35:25.080
that allows us to go from a short-term

01:35:25.080 --> 01:35:26.097
to a long-term memory,

01:35:26.097 --> 01:35:28.860
and what's that kind of plasticity.

01:35:28.860 --> 01:35:32.510
Because it's both,

01:35:32.510 --> 01:35:34.160
there's that

01:35:34.160 --> 01:35:37.480
wonderful thing about
being a child that you can

01:35:37.480 --> 01:35:39.080
learn new languages,

01:35:39.080 --> 01:35:43.540
you can learn how to play the violin

01:35:43.540 --> 01:35:45.710
much more easily than when you're older,

01:35:45.710 --> 01:35:47.070
and there is that kind of

01:35:48.730 --> 01:35:52.140
a little bit of a shrinking
down of that plasticity.

01:35:52.140 --> 01:35:53.600
It's not all or none,

01:35:53.600 --> 01:35:55.990
and we see people all over who continue,

01:35:55.990 --> 01:35:57.360
and there are all these things

01:35:57.360 --> 01:35:58.450
that show that if you

01:36:00.370 --> 01:36:02.680
listen to music, if you dance,

01:36:02.680 --> 01:36:06.170
if you do crosswords, you read,

01:36:06.170 --> 01:36:07.660
that you keep that going.

01:36:07.660 --> 01:36:11.010
But I do think it's something
that happens with aging,

01:36:11.010 --> 01:36:13.373
you lose some of that brain plasticity.

01:36:14.290 --> 01:36:15.880
You have all the old-term memories

01:36:15.880 --> 01:36:17.030
because they're already stored.

01:36:17.030 --> 01:36:18.580
You just don't have that ability

01:36:18.580 --> 01:36:20.400
to like change the circuit.

01:36:22.158 --> 01:36:24.810
- And I think also the encounter,

01:36:24.810 --> 01:36:28.260
what we also remember is our
first encounter with something,

01:36:28.260 --> 01:36:30.740
or our first encounter with someone.

01:36:30.740 --> 01:36:33.020
And so it's when everything is new

01:36:33.020 --> 01:36:34.710
that we actually remember it.

01:36:34.710 --> 01:36:38.750
Our experience in
discovery is so profound.

01:36:38.750 --> 01:36:40.460
And once you stop discovering,

01:36:40.460 --> 01:36:41.790
once something isn't knew,

01:36:41.790 --> 01:36:45.040
it's hard to create a new memory,

01:36:45.040 --> 01:36:47.270
because you're actually repeating what...

01:36:48.630 --> 01:36:49.690
Forgive me for saying this,

01:36:49.690 --> 01:36:54.230
but my mother who's really
forgetting a lot these days,

01:36:54.230 --> 01:36:57.113
is in a place where people
are helping to care for her.

01:36:58.780 --> 01:37:01.780
They have a trip in a bus

01:37:01.780 --> 01:37:05.770
in the afternoons to go out
to the beach in San Francisco,

01:37:05.770 --> 01:37:07.103
and see the Golden Gate.

01:37:08.540 --> 01:37:11.433
And my mother said to me two days ago,

01:37:12.307 --> 01:37:13.140
"I've seen the water.

01:37:13.140 --> 01:37:14.107
"I've seen the beach.

01:37:14.107 --> 01:37:15.957
"I don't need to see those things."

01:37:18.300 --> 01:37:20.490
And it's very intense because what is it

01:37:20.490 --> 01:37:23.593
when you tell yourself
it's not a new experience.

01:37:24.810 --> 01:37:28.343
You stop creating new experience.

01:37:32.070 --> 01:37:33.288
- Thank you.

